410→                           Erdős originally asked Mahler whether there are infinitely many pairs of consecutive powerful numbers, but Mahler immediately observed that the answer is yes from the infinitely many solutions to the Pell equation $x^2=2^3y^2+1$. <br><br>The list of $n$ such that $n$ and $n+1$ are both powerful is <a href="https://oeis.org/A060355" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">A060355</a> in the OEIS.<br><br>The answer to the first question is no: Golomb <a href="#cite-Go70-365" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Go70','365'); return false;">[Go70]</a> observed that both $12167=23^3$ and $12168=2^33^213^2$ are powerful. Walker <a href="#cite-Wa76-365" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Wa76','365'); return false;">[Wa76]</a> proved that the equation\[7^3x^2=3^3y^2+1\]has infinitely many solutions, giving infinitely many counterexamples.<br><br>See also <a href="/364" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[364]</a>.<br><br>This is discussed in problem B16 of Guy's collection <a href="#cite-Gu04-365" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Gu04','365'); return false;">[Gu04]</a>.
